Sure.

00:04:24.359 --> 00:04:33.320
So my name is Leanne, I'm at Roam Therapeutics, and I started here in my current role about

00:04:33.320 --> 00:04:38.000
seven or eight months ago, so I'm still relatively new.

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:44.040
So Roam Therapeutics is a small biotech company based in Boston.

00:04:44.040 --> 00:04:50.640
And what we are studying is what we call, well, what some people call the dark genome.

00:04:50.640 --> 00:04:56.679
So if you think about the human genome, we're all pretty familiar now with the genes that

00:04:56.679 --> 00:05:02.720
code proteins and have functions that are relatively well studied.

00:05:03.119 --> 00:05:07.760
But there has been, I think, an increasing appreciation for things that are not protein

00:05:07.760 --> 00:05:09.880
coding genes.

00:05:09.880 --> 00:05:16.880
And I think that this is an area of study which is, it's challenging from like a computational

00:05:16.880 --> 00:05:17.880
perspective.

00:05:17.880 --> 00:05:23.000
You know, how do you quantify these kinds of elements which have special challenges

00:05:23.000 --> 00:05:25.279
which we can talk about?

00:05:25.279 --> 00:05:31.160
And then on top of that, how do you, you know, relate that to potential new therapies?

00:05:31.160 --> 00:05:32.760
And so I think it's a really exciting space.

00:05:32.760 --> 00:05:34.480
I'm really excited to be here.

00:05:34.480 --> 00:05:37.079
I'm happy to talk about that more.

00:05:37.079 --> 00:05:41.920
My background, it's going all the way back to college, I guess.

00:05:41.920 --> 00:05:49.200
I studied mathematics, and I think I minored in Chinese language.

00:05:49.200 --> 00:05:56.600
So I spent some time in China, you know, just, I think I spent an entire semester just taking

00:05:56.600 --> 00:06:01.559
language and literature classes, which was really fun and totally different.

00:06:01.559 --> 00:06:05.559
I think that was my final semester in my senior year.

00:06:05.559 --> 00:06:08.279
So that was very exciting.

00:06:08.279 --> 00:06:12.640
But before that, it was really just math all the time.

00:06:12.640 --> 00:06:19.480
And the idea that I had had when I was in college was to just pursue math.

00:06:19.480 --> 00:06:25.239
And I was really not interested in biology, to the chagrin of my mother who wanted me

00:06:25.399 --> 00:06:33.160
to become a doctor and study pre-med and go that track, you know, all the way to the end.

00:06:33.160 --> 00:06:40.119
I did try for, I think, a semester or a year, and I thought that biology was just, it's

00:06:40.119 --> 00:06:41.119
just a hot mess.

00:06:41.119 --> 00:06:43.760
No one knew what was going on.

00:06:43.760 --> 00:06:50.720
And it was just very, it was not very satisfying compared to the kinds of problems that I was

00:06:50.720 --> 00:06:55.559
trying to solve in my math classes, which were clean and well-defined, and you can,

00:06:55.559 --> 00:06:59.559
you know, write a proof and it was either true or it wasn't true, right?

00:06:59.559 --> 00:07:07.079
In biology, you don't have those kinds of, it's not very binary.

00:07:07.079 --> 00:07:12.920
And so I, you know, I really was very set on this all the way through to basically my

00:07:12.920 --> 00:07:14.079
senior year.

00:07:14.079 --> 00:07:18.519
And then in my senior year, I had to think about what to do next.

00:07:18.519 --> 00:07:21.079
And I wasn't ready to get a job.

00:07:21.079 --> 00:07:26.880
So I thought, well, I have to go to grad school then because I have no other skills.

00:07:26.880 --> 00:07:32.279
So I was applying to graduate school and I applied to a bunch of math programs, but then

00:07:32.279 --> 00:07:38.000
I also ended up applying to some bioinformatics programs, even though that wasn't something

00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:41.000
I had really studied before.

00:07:41.000 --> 00:07:46.760
It was something that I sort of became interested in, in some of these summer undergraduate

00:07:46.760 --> 00:07:48.519
research programs.

00:07:48.519 --> 00:07:53.600
So I was a math major, but then I tried, you know, for a month or two to study a little

00:07:53.600 --> 00:07:55.480
bit of genomics.

00:07:55.480 --> 00:08:01.920
And with genomics, I thought that was something that was cleaner than biology, but was still

00:08:01.920 --> 00:08:04.399
applicable in the real world.

00:08:04.399 --> 00:08:10.559
And so that was, you know, it kind of piqued my interest and it felt like it was the best

00:08:10.559 --> 00:08:16.519
of both worlds because towards the end of my undergraduate career, I was beginning to

00:08:16.519 --> 00:08:20.200
think that pure mathematics, which is what I was studying, it wasn't applied math, it

00:08:20.200 --> 00:08:27.079
was pure math, was becoming less satisfying because I just couldn't see how what I was

00:08:27.079 --> 00:08:33.840
studying day-to-day had any impact on, you know, what I saw day-to-day, you know, the

00:08:33.840 --> 00:08:35.179
lives that we were living.

00:08:35.179 --> 00:08:39.520
So that became less interesting to me.

00:08:39.520 --> 00:08:44.200
But I applied to a couple of bioinformatics programs and, you know, I got into a few of

00:08:44.200 --> 00:08:48.039
them and I decided just to make the jump.

00:08:48.039 --> 00:08:53.760
You know, I had no idea really what I was getting myself into, but I was ready to pull

00:08:53.760 --> 00:08:56.679
the triggers, so I just went.

00:08:56.679 --> 00:09:03.400
And that's really how I ended up in computational biology slash bioinformatics.

00:09:03.400 --> 00:09:09.159
So it's kind of a long-winded story of how I got here, but I'm really happy to be here.

00:09:09.799 --> 00:09:15.919
I think it really makes use of, you know, some of my skill set from my math background,

00:09:15.919 --> 00:09:23.840
but also, you know, I've come to appreciate more and more that even though biology, I

00:09:23.840 --> 00:09:28.960
guess it's more that I appreciate the complexity of biology now more than I did before.

00:09:28.960 --> 00:09:34.760
I think before I was really turned off by it and kind of scared and I didn't know how

00:09:34.760 --> 00:09:36.520
to interpret anything.

00:09:36.520 --> 00:09:45.400
But I think over the years, I think that unknowingness has become more exciting rather than scary.

00:09:45.400 --> 00:09:51.739
Thank you so much for that intro into your journey.

00:09:51.739 --> 00:09:55.520
What about something that you like to do outside of work too?

00:09:55.520 --> 00:10:00.479
Yeah, that has really changed a lot over the years.

00:10:00.479 --> 00:10:03.880
You know, now I have two little kids.

00:10:03.880 --> 00:10:08.080
They're both in daycare, so they're not school-aged yet.

00:10:08.080 --> 00:10:13.099
And I spend most of my day sitting in front of a computer, you know, doing this.

00:10:13.099 --> 00:10:18.559
So what I like to do outside of work is really to get outside, to get moving.

00:10:18.559 --> 00:10:19.559
So I run.

00:10:19.559 --> 00:10:25.760
I've been running for maybe like 20 plus years now.

00:10:25.760 --> 00:10:28.039
It's really, I'm not fast.

00:10:28.039 --> 00:10:30.239
I don't run to race.

00:10:30.239 --> 00:10:31.760
I run to be outside.

00:10:31.760 --> 00:10:35.919
I run for the feeling of running.

00:10:35.919 --> 00:10:42.479
You know, I think one of my best graduate school friends was also a big runner.

00:10:42.479 --> 00:10:48.340
And I think that she put it really well when she described why she enjoyed running.

00:10:48.340 --> 00:10:52.400
You know, she really treated it almost as like a meditation activity.

00:10:52.400 --> 00:10:57.960
We used to go for these long runs and you just get all of the stuff that you were thinking

00:10:57.960 --> 00:11:02.039
about that was percolating in your head, you know, all day or all night, you get it

00:11:02.039 --> 00:11:06.200
out and you get the endorphins instead.

00:11:06.200 --> 00:11:11.599
And it really helps to clear my mind, especially when I'm like really stuck on a problem and

00:11:11.599 --> 00:11:12.919
I'm feeling really frustrated.

00:11:12.919 --> 00:11:14.320
It really helps.

00:11:14.320 --> 00:11:15.320
Yeah.

00:11:15.320 --> 00:11:16.320
It's fun.

00:11:16.320 --> 00:11:20.200
It's fun to see what are the common hobbies among this group, because running is definitely

00:11:20.200 --> 00:11:21.200
one of them.

00:11:21.200 --> 00:11:23.200
And then playing music is definitely.

00:11:23.200 --> 00:11:24.200
Yeah.

00:11:24.200 --> 00:11:25.200
Yeah.

00:11:25.440 --> 00:11:30.799
I've been playing piano for many, many years, but I started drifting away from piano when

00:11:30.799 --> 00:11:35.919
I started doing more computer work because after the end of a long day, I don't want

00:11:35.919 --> 00:11:41.239
to sit again in front of something I want to be moving around.

00:11:41.239 --> 00:11:42.239
Yeah.

00:11:42.239 --> 00:11:46.559
Well, I was I was wondering, you mentioned a bit about the dark genome, but for some

00:11:46.559 --> 00:11:51.799
of us without a biology background, would you be able to explain a little bit more about

00:11:51.799 --> 00:11:56.400
the dark genome and about the the work you're doing at Rome?

00:11:56.400 --> 00:11:57.400
Mm hmm.

00:11:57.400 --> 00:11:58.400
Yeah.

00:11:58.400 --> 00:12:04.719
So I think probably everyone has learned in school this central dogma of, you know, we

00:12:04.719 --> 00:12:05.719
have our DNA.

00:12:05.719 --> 00:12:13.440
It encodes, you know, genes which get transcribed into RNA and then RNA gets turned into protein

00:12:13.440 --> 00:12:18.039
and that the protein is the stuff that does stuff in our body.

00:12:18.039 --> 00:12:22.000
And I think that that has been the dogma for many, many years.

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:27.359
But the the percentage of our genome that encodes these protein coding genes is actually

00:12:27.359 --> 00:12:28.960
really small.

00:12:28.960 --> 00:12:33.200
So most of our DNA is not coding for that.

00:12:33.200 --> 00:12:39.419
And I think that we're, you know, we're still sort of learning what else is there.

00:12:39.419 --> 00:12:44.280
So these non protein coding genes, I think, for a long time have been described as junk

00:12:44.280 --> 00:12:45.280
DNA.

00:12:46.000 --> 00:12:49.479
But we called it junk because we didn't know what it was doing.

00:12:49.479 --> 00:12:57.359
And so at Rome, you know, we're very specifically focused on this class of elements called repetitive

00:12:57.359 --> 00:12:58.799
elements.

00:12:58.799 --> 00:13:05.039
So, you know, we have like one copy of gene A, maybe two copies of gene B.

00:13:05.039 --> 00:13:09.919
But then there are these elements where we have like hundreds of thousands of copies

00:13:09.919 --> 00:13:12.559
of basically the same element.

00:13:12.559 --> 00:13:13.559
It's like a gene.

00:13:13.840 --> 00:13:16.840
It may or may not encode protein.

00:13:16.840 --> 00:13:24.099
And some of these elements have the ability to lift themselves up and make new copies

00:13:24.099 --> 00:13:25.599
in our genome.

00:13:25.599 --> 00:13:28.080
It's very cool.

00:13:28.080 --> 00:13:34.059
But we don't really understand like the full implications of what they're doing.

00:13:34.059 --> 00:13:40.719
And so we think, you know, especially in the last, I don't know, maybe five or 10, 10 years,

00:13:40.719 --> 00:13:46.719
people have been starting to appreciate that they're playing a role in potentially cancer,

00:13:46.719 --> 00:13:49.599
in autoimmune disease, in inflammation.

00:13:49.599 --> 00:13:56.239
And so at Rome, we're, you know, thinking about these elements and not only what roles

00:13:56.239 --> 00:14:03.659
they play, but, you know, in which human diseases could they be causal, or maybe a biomarker

00:14:03.659 --> 00:14:13.299
of disease, and where we can potentially impact human health for the better.

00:14:13.299 --> 00:14:14.299
Is that helpful?

00:14:14.299 --> 00:14:15.299
Yeah, that is helpful.

00:14:15.299 --> 00:14:20.539
I know, Bill, you had, I think, a follow-up question here on dark genomics.

00:14:20.539 --> 00:14:22.940
Bill, do you want to jump in?

00:14:22.940 --> 00:14:25.539
You want me to read it?

00:14:25.539 --> 00:14:28.739
I can read it.

00:14:28.739 --> 00:14:33.659
But the question was, with dark genomics, are you using the same widely used suppliers

00:14:33.659 --> 00:14:39.099
of sequencing machines, or are you developing new software related to new hardware?

00:14:39.099 --> 00:14:46.140
Yeah, so the sequencing technology itself, we're primarily using the same sequencing

00:14:46.140 --> 00:14:47.140
technology.

00:14:47.140 --> 00:14:50.780
So, you know, there's short-read sequencing and long-read sequencing, there are kinds

00:14:50.780 --> 00:14:55.780
of pros and cons of both for looking at these repetitive elements.

00:14:55.820 --> 00:15:01.700
I think the challenge is, I mean, in part the technology, but really what we are focused

00:15:01.700 --> 00:15:08.260
on is downstream of that in the quantification algorithms, and the algorithms to detect where

00:15:08.260 --> 00:15:13.099
new elements are being inserted, which weren't there previously.

00:15:13.099 --> 00:15:16.099
So a lot of this is algorithmic development.

00:15:16.099 --> 00:15:22.460
And you know, I didn't build any of these algorithms, these were here when I joined.

00:15:22.460 --> 00:15:26.299
But we have some really, really excellent computational scientists who have been at

00:15:26.299 --> 00:15:30.780
Rome for, you know, a couple of years now, who have really built up this platform.

00:15:30.780 --> 00:15:36.700
Yeah, Travis, I see you just put a question in the chat, want to jump in next?

00:15:36.700 --> 00:15:37.700
Sure.

00:15:37.700 --> 00:15:41.700
Hey, it's cool to meet you.

00:15:41.700 --> 00:15:46.179
I spent some time thinking about long non-coding RNAs in prostate cancer in a very academic

00:15:46.179 --> 00:15:47.179
setting.

00:15:47.419 --> 00:15:53.500
And since then, I've moved over to kind of CRO world, much like where you operate at

00:15:53.500 --> 00:15:54.500
Rome.

00:15:54.500 --> 00:15:57.419
I'm curious about your business pipeline, like the research pipeline.

00:15:57.419 --> 00:16:02.419
So what proportion of it there happens by virtue of kind of computational discovery

00:16:02.419 --> 00:16:03.500
only?

00:16:03.500 --> 00:16:05.020
And then where does that data come from?

00:16:05.020 --> 00:16:10.659
Like, so in the in academic setting, it was a lot of kind of epidemiological studies and

00:16:10.659 --> 00:16:15.179
specimens collected, we do deep sequencing, and then we kind of try to infer through ML

00:16:15.179 --> 00:16:18.820
and other techniques, what kinds of targets in the dark genome might be relevant.

00:16:18.820 --> 00:16:22.619
But you'll have a different kind of pipeline, you do a lot of my studies, is there other

00:16:22.619 --> 00:16:25.219
in kind of in vitro work that you do?

00:16:25.219 --> 00:16:32.979
Yeah, so it depends on, I guess, how far along the asset is, you know, so we have, you know,

00:16:32.979 --> 00:16:35.580
assets that are approaching the clinic very soon.

00:16:35.580 --> 00:16:39.179
And then we have assets that are like early, early development, right.

00:16:39.179 --> 00:16:47.299
And so depending on where we are, in terms of how far along clinically, I think it changes,

00:16:47.299 --> 00:16:49.219
you know, what kind of research we do.

00:16:49.219 --> 00:16:56.299
So for our lead program, our PT 2950, we're going after autoimmune disease, and specifically

00:16:56.299 --> 00:16:58.219
cutaneous lupus.

00:16:58.219 --> 00:17:02.260
And so, you know, a lot of research has already been done there.

00:17:02.260 --> 00:17:07.420
And we've done like, for example, a lot of in vivo and in vitro studies, and some ex

00:17:07.459 --> 00:17:12.579
vivo studies, which are really interesting, where you actually, so this is they're like

00:17:12.579 --> 00:17:17.900
a CRO that does this, where they take these skin samples, which have been excised from

00:17:17.900 --> 00:17:20.819
patients undergoing like cosmetic surgery.

00:17:20.819 --> 00:17:26.939
And then they can, you know, grow, not necessarily grow, but like keep them alive in a in a dish.

00:17:26.939 --> 00:17:33.099
And you can treat them with different things with like, with UV or your compounds or whatever.

00:17:33.099 --> 00:17:36.739
And then you can sort of see what changes in terms of their gene expression, you can

00:17:36.739 --> 00:17:43.819
even profile, like with imaging technology, like how the skin changes over that period

00:17:43.819 --> 00:17:46.140
of time, it's really cool.

00:17:46.140 --> 00:17:51.380
For like early discovery things, when we're looking for new indications and new targets,

00:17:51.380 --> 00:17:55.380
that's where I think you have to do, you have to kind of take a step back, because you don't

00:17:55.380 --> 00:17:57.859
know exactly what you're looking for there, right.

00:17:57.859 --> 00:18:02.739
And so I think that in part is driven by computational discovery.

00:18:02.739 --> 00:18:11.699
So we've processed, I don't know how many, like 10s of 1000s of samples, maybe 100,000

00:18:11.699 --> 00:18:17.020
samples at this point, of public data, all across different kinds of indications, all

00:18:17.020 --> 00:18:23.459
across your, you know, your your gold standard data sets, like TCGA, GTEx, and you know,

00:18:23.459 --> 00:18:31.339
those kinds of data sets, and a bunch of different indications from studies in public databases

00:18:31.339 --> 00:18:32.819
like GEO.

00:18:32.819 --> 00:18:38.219
And then there, we look for, you know, any indication of activity of the targets that

00:18:38.219 --> 00:18:43.099
we're interested in, and also genes which are related to activity.

00:18:43.099 --> 00:18:44.099
That's cool.

00:18:44.099 --> 00:18:48.219
So in your team, do you have like a small army of people who are just cranking on TCGA,

00:18:48.219 --> 00:18:52.699
GTEx, and GEO, like all day long, sounds like the academics dream, you know,

00:18:52.699 --> 00:18:55.180
We need a bigger, we need a bigger army.

00:18:55.579 --> 00:18:56.780
Army's never big enough.

00:18:58.540 --> 00:18:59.739
But yes, more or less.

00:19:00.619 --> 00:19:06.540
You know, that's, I think that's one of the fun slash frustrating parts of being in a

00:19:06.540 --> 00:19:07.500
small company.

00:19:07.500 --> 00:19:08.540
Like Rome is small.

00:19:09.500 --> 00:19:16.140
I think in total, now we have like 30, 30 something people, and the computational group

00:19:16.140 --> 00:19:17.420
is me and three scientists.

00:19:18.939 --> 00:19:24.939
And so you can imagine the amount of work that it takes to develop and then maintain

00:19:24.939 --> 00:19:30.060
the pipeline, and then do the analysis, and then like continually trying to improve that

00:19:30.060 --> 00:19:30.540
pipeline.

00:19:30.540 --> 00:19:32.939
It's a lot of work, and we get stretched pretty thin.

00:19:33.979 --> 00:19:37.180
So prioritization is, is really important.

00:19:37.180 --> 00:19:40.459
And your priorities are going to change from day to day.

00:19:41.420 --> 00:19:41.979
Cool.

00:19:41.979 --> 00:19:42.300
Thanks.

00:19:42.300 --> 00:19:46.939
And not to jeopardize all the quick, but then the skin, the skin, what xenographs, I guess

00:19:46.939 --> 00:19:48.459
you call them maybe, like, what do you do?

00:19:48.459 --> 00:19:50.380
Do you like give them sunburns and stuff?

00:19:51.020 --> 00:19:51.520
Yeah.

00:19:52.400 --> 00:19:55.839
I was, I was at a colleague who had like a whole basement full of, I mean, it's not a

00:19:55.839 --> 00:19:56.160
basement.

00:19:56.160 --> 00:19:58.079
It was like a research lab full of many brains.

00:19:58.079 --> 00:19:58.560
He called them.

00:19:58.560 --> 00:19:59.520
It was very X files.

00:20:00.079 --> 00:20:00.579
Yeah.

00:20:02.000 --> 00:20:05.119
And you always wonder, like, are there, do they have consciousness?

00:20:05.119 --> 00:20:07.359
They're like living in these little petri dishes brains.

00:20:07.359 --> 00:20:08.400
It's like weird.

00:20:09.599 --> 00:20:11.199
Yeah, that's very cool.

00:20:11.199 --> 00:20:16.400
Now, I had not heard about this kind of assay until it was run and we were analyzing the

00:20:16.400 --> 00:20:18.959
results just maybe a couple months ago.

00:20:19.280 --> 00:20:23.760
I know you, you actually just talked a bit about prioritizing and that was actually a

00:20:23.760 --> 00:20:26.160
question I wanted to ask you here.

00:20:26.160 --> 00:20:32.560
So out of a company with 30 something people, how do you prioritize projects and allocate

00:20:32.560 --> 00:20:33.280
resources?

00:20:35.839 --> 00:20:37.040
It's a really good question.

00:20:38.640 --> 00:20:40.880
And the answer should not be haphazardly.

00:20:41.599 --> 00:20:47.760
You know, I think that you really need to have a high level understanding of what the

00:20:47.760 --> 00:20:51.839
timelines are for the company and what's driving those timelines.

00:20:51.839 --> 00:20:52.400
Right.

00:20:52.400 --> 00:20:58.800
So you have to kind of take a top-down approach and okay, I'm going to, I'm going to diverge

00:20:58.800 --> 00:21:00.239
a little bit and tell an anecdote.

00:21:01.280 --> 00:21:04.079
Both of my parents are university professors.

00:21:04.079 --> 00:21:07.119
And so my dad teaches mathematics, so pure math.

00:21:07.119 --> 00:21:09.359
And my mom is a professor of statistics.

00:21:10.400 --> 00:21:15.680
And I remember when I was describing, you know, my day-to-day because they've only been

00:21:15.680 --> 00:21:19.760
in the academic world and they're like, you know, what do you, what do you do every day?

00:21:19.760 --> 00:21:22.880
And I'm like, well, I sit in like five or six hours of meetings every day.

00:21:22.880 --> 00:21:26.319
And they're like, what do you, why do you need to sit in so many meetings?

00:21:26.319 --> 00:21:27.520
Like, what are you doing?

00:21:28.800 --> 00:21:34.000
And I think a lot of it is just, you know, getting everyone and all the teams, like these

00:21:34.000 --> 00:21:40.079
very disparate teams doing very disparate activities on the same page, because you have

00:21:40.079 --> 00:21:46.719
to drive forward these programs where you need biology to run biology experiments.

00:21:46.719 --> 00:21:51.040
You need computational folks like myself to run computational experiments.

00:21:51.040 --> 00:21:53.839
You need chemistry to make the chemical matter.

00:21:54.959 --> 00:22:00.239
And trying to get everyone on the same page to agree on what is the best path forward.

00:22:00.959 --> 00:22:08.239
What is, you know, what are the go, no-go decisions and what are the timelines in terms of,

00:22:09.040 --> 00:22:13.839
yeah, so what are the timelines and how long can your company survive for, you know,

00:22:13.839 --> 00:22:15.520
especially as a small company?

00:22:16.719 --> 00:22:17.839
That part is really important.

00:22:17.839 --> 00:22:19.119
So that takes a lot of effort.

00:22:20.079 --> 00:22:25.119
You don't necessarily have to think about that in an academic setting as much.

00:22:25.760 --> 00:22:29.359
So even though my dad was the chair of the math department for many years,

00:22:30.400 --> 00:22:33.839
he had to deal with, you know, some of this, what they call politicking, right?

00:22:34.640 --> 00:22:35.920
Getting everyone on the same page.

00:22:35.920 --> 00:22:41.280
But it's like Professor A and Professor B are working on two completely different things.

00:22:41.280 --> 00:22:45.599
They don't have to, you know, get together and talk about what are you doing today?

00:22:45.599 --> 00:22:46.479
What are you doing today?

00:22:46.479 --> 00:22:47.839
What are you doing next week?

00:22:48.479 --> 00:22:50.400
They don't have to align on those kinds of things.

00:22:51.520 --> 00:22:54.079
And it turns out that alignment takes a lot of time.

00:22:55.040 --> 00:22:55.599
Absolutely.

00:22:56.719 --> 00:22:59.520
Nellie, I see you had a question in the chat here.

00:22:59.520 --> 00:23:00.319
Want to jump in?

00:23:02.959 --> 00:23:03.459
Sure.

00:23:04.800 --> 00:23:08.800
Thanks, Leanne, for sharing about your journey.

00:23:09.839 --> 00:23:13.760
I studied biology in undergrad, as well as economics.

00:23:14.400 --> 00:23:19.839
And now I've been working in finance in a data science role for a few years, about five years.

00:23:20.079 --> 00:23:25.359
And something I've always thought about was transitioning back over to the intersection

00:23:25.359 --> 00:23:27.199
of data science and biology.

00:23:28.560 --> 00:23:34.880
But I do know there's definitely a lot of need for higher degrees.

00:23:34.880 --> 00:23:40.160
And I was curious what you thought, you know, are certain things that individuals should

00:23:40.160 --> 00:23:45.280
take into account if they're interested in moving over to the sciences and away from

00:23:45.280 --> 00:23:46.959
a traditional data science role?

00:23:47.280 --> 00:23:48.880
Traditional finance, I guess.

00:23:50.160 --> 00:23:53.280
Yeah, I don't know much about finance.

00:23:54.880 --> 00:24:00.560
But I do know that people, at least early on, you know, when I was in grad school, people

00:24:00.560 --> 00:24:06.160
made this change between going the finance route and going the bioinformatics route.

00:24:06.160 --> 00:24:08.319
They made it pretty fluidly at the time.

00:24:09.199 --> 00:24:13.839
I think that that's probably different after you've been in the workforce for a little

00:24:13.839 --> 00:24:14.400
while.

00:24:14.479 --> 00:24:18.959
So I think after that, it becomes a little bit more challenging, but it's not impossible.

00:24:20.560 --> 00:24:25.680
Especially if you're willing to start in like an entry level role.

00:24:26.719 --> 00:24:28.479
I think that's entirely possible.

00:24:28.479 --> 00:24:34.400
And I think that, and I'm biased here, but, you know, one of the things that I love about

00:24:34.400 --> 00:24:40.239
working in startups is that, you know, you don't have to have a lot of experience.

00:24:40.239 --> 00:24:47.040
One of the things that I love about working in startups is that, well, okay, I don't want

00:24:47.040 --> 00:24:52.000
to say the wrong thing, but I think that one of the benefits of working in a startup is

00:24:52.000 --> 00:25:03.199
that you can start a role and not have like very, very deep and narrow knowledge in a

00:25:03.199 --> 00:25:04.000
particular role.

00:25:04.560 --> 00:25:10.400
I think what you typically need to be able to do in a startup environment is to play

00:25:10.400 --> 00:25:13.359
many different roles and start up very quickly.

00:25:14.160 --> 00:25:21.359
So I'll give a little bit of an example from my own experience, which is not quite what

00:25:21.359 --> 00:25:24.959
you're, you know, what you're talking about, but I think it has some relation.

00:25:25.680 --> 00:25:32.079
So in my first industry job, I was at a place called Ceres Therapeutics and we were very,

00:25:32.400 --> 00:25:35.599
I mean, we were a microbiome therapeutics company.

00:25:35.599 --> 00:25:39.040
And so I worked there for almost six years.

00:25:39.839 --> 00:25:44.000
And when I was there, everything was about microbial profiling.

00:25:44.719 --> 00:25:47.359
And, you know, we were like processing stool samples.

00:25:47.359 --> 00:25:49.760
We were thinking about what is the best algorithm?

00:25:49.760 --> 00:25:54.800
What is the best database for determining what kinds of bacteria are in a sample?

00:25:56.560 --> 00:26:00.239
Nothing like human data related at all, basically.

00:26:00.959 --> 00:26:06.239
And towards the end of that, I was thinking, you know, I wanted to broaden my experience

00:26:06.239 --> 00:26:13.520
a bit to, you know, working in like to learn more about oncology, to broaden outside of

00:26:13.520 --> 00:26:14.640
the microbiome space.

00:26:15.359 --> 00:26:21.920
And, you know, it's not like I could jump directly into, you know, like a principal

00:26:21.920 --> 00:26:26.719
scientist or senior director of oncology at one of these small startup companies, right?

00:26:26.719 --> 00:26:28.160
Because I didn't have the experience.

00:26:28.880 --> 00:26:35.040
And so I ended up going to a small company that didn't have a bioinformatics function

00:26:35.040 --> 00:26:35.439
at all.

00:26:36.079 --> 00:26:41.280
And so I got to, you know, A, learn how to build up that bioinformatics infrastructure,

00:26:41.280 --> 00:26:42.800
spin it up in the cloud.

00:26:42.800 --> 00:26:50.000
But B, at the same time, I had a mentor who basically took a chance on me and gave me

00:26:50.000 --> 00:26:54.160
a little bit of time to sort of ramp up on oncology.

00:26:54.160 --> 00:26:57.599
You know, how do people think about, you know, problems in oncology?

00:26:58.479 --> 00:27:03.119
Specifically, I was in this space called the Antibody Drug Conjugates.

00:27:03.680 --> 00:27:07.839
So that was completely out of my wheelhouse at the time.

00:27:09.280 --> 00:27:12.880
But it's not something that you can't learn, right?

00:27:12.880 --> 00:27:18.959
So I think, you know, what's really important is to understand your own capacity for learning

00:27:18.959 --> 00:27:19.680
new things.

00:27:20.800 --> 00:27:24.880
And I think that if you're confident that you have that capacity, that you can do it.

00:27:25.439 --> 00:27:27.439
It's just how much effort is it going to take?

00:27:28.479 --> 00:27:30.640
And are you willing to commit that effort?

00:27:30.640 --> 00:27:35.199
But I'm a strong believer in that, especially in startup spaces, because, you know, one

00:27:35.199 --> 00:27:38.239
day this company is going to be here, and one day it's not, you're going to have to

00:27:38.239 --> 00:27:41.760
go somewhere else and probably pick up new skills while you're at it.

00:27:44.000 --> 00:27:49.760
I know that's probably not like super helpful, but I think it's possible is my answer.

00:27:50.479 --> 00:27:56.800
And it's just about finding, you know, the time to do some training on your own, but

00:27:56.800 --> 00:28:02.560
also finding the right fit in terms of a new job, you know, in the space that you're

00:28:02.560 --> 00:28:03.599
interested in going into.

00:28:05.839 --> 00:28:06.400
That's great.

00:28:06.400 --> 00:28:07.199
Thank you so much.

00:28:09.359 --> 00:28:16.800
And I think also once you know yourself that you have that capacity to learn, how do you

00:28:16.800 --> 00:28:23.760
then show the hiring manager at this other role that you do have, and that's the benefit?

00:28:24.400 --> 00:28:25.199
Yeah.

00:28:25.199 --> 00:28:27.199
A lot of it is trying to draw parallels.

00:28:27.839 --> 00:28:30.400
So maybe you don't have a specific skill.

00:28:30.400 --> 00:28:33.040
You haven't done this particular analysis before.

00:28:33.680 --> 00:28:38.640
But in data science, you know, one of the great things is that if you're working with

00:28:38.640 --> 00:28:43.599
data, you just have to know what kind of data it is in order to know how to treat it and

00:28:43.599 --> 00:28:45.199
how to do the analysis, right?

00:28:45.199 --> 00:28:50.800
So maybe I haven't, you know, done an analysis with human gene expression before, but I've

00:28:50.800 --> 00:28:54.560
done a lot of bacterial, you know, composition analysis.

00:28:54.560 --> 00:28:56.400
So you can draw those kinds of parallels.

00:28:57.839 --> 00:29:02.719
And I think it's easier to do that in the data science space than in some other spaces.

00:29:05.359 --> 00:29:05.760
Thank you.

00:29:06.959 --> 00:29:09.359
Svetlana, I see you had a question a little bit earlier.

00:29:09.359 --> 00:29:10.560
Want to jump in here next?

00:29:12.800 --> 00:29:13.520
Yeah, thank you.

00:29:15.280 --> 00:29:22.719
Yeah, so my question was about computational biology and bioinformatics versus data science.

00:29:22.719 --> 00:29:26.640
So my background is actually a bit similar to yours.

00:29:26.640 --> 00:29:37.439
I had a computational biology slash bioinformatics degree and then a little bit of postdoc

00:29:37.439 --> 00:29:38.319
experience.

00:29:38.319 --> 00:29:40.880
And then I transitioned to data science.

00:29:40.880 --> 00:29:48.800
But I feel like that it's, for me, it's always kind of, so I'm not doing bioinformatics anymore

00:29:48.800 --> 00:29:55.040
because I feel like I probably don't want to, or maybe I was a bit too traumatized with

00:29:55.040 --> 00:29:59.920
like the academia experience and like working in the lab and like all of this.

00:30:00.640 --> 00:30:02.719
But I sometimes think of going back.

00:30:02.719 --> 00:30:08.319
But I'm curious because I was also like looking at your profile, right?

00:30:08.319 --> 00:30:12.719
So right now you're director of data science, right?

00:30:12.719 --> 00:30:19.839
But so do you feel that this role is different or is it because like you have data science

00:30:19.839 --> 00:30:27.280
in your title or it is still more like computational biology but just named as a data science?

00:30:28.079 --> 00:30:29.280
Definitely the latter.

00:30:29.280 --> 00:30:34.400
This is a trend in the industry that I really only noticed in the last couple of years.

00:30:35.040 --> 00:30:40.560
You know, five, six, seven years ago when I was getting started, everything was comp

00:30:40.560 --> 00:30:42.319
bio, bioinformatics.

00:30:42.319 --> 00:30:47.839
And then in the last couple of years, I started seeing everyone's title started shifting towards

00:30:47.839 --> 00:30:48.880
being data science.

00:30:50.640 --> 00:30:52.560
I don't know what was driving that trend.

00:30:53.119 --> 00:30:56.479
I still consider what I do computational biology.

00:30:57.839 --> 00:31:03.439
You know, maybe people want to say data science because it seems to have more like broader

00:31:03.439 --> 00:31:04.640
implications.

00:31:04.640 --> 00:31:09.760
So we do more than just, you know, genomic pipelines, for example, like we analyze all

00:31:09.760 --> 00:31:10.880
kinds of data.

00:31:10.880 --> 00:31:14.880
So in that sense, OK, you know, data science, that's fine.

00:31:15.920 --> 00:31:18.719
But it's definitely still the same thing.

00:31:20.319 --> 00:31:21.920
Yeah, interesting.

00:31:21.920 --> 00:31:29.359
But so would you say that so at your company, for example, yeah, there is no other data

00:31:29.359 --> 00:31:30.079
science, right?

00:31:30.079 --> 00:31:31.199
No, there isn't.

00:31:31.920 --> 00:31:36.800
The kind of separation that I've seen, which is more typical, I think, is within is like

00:31:36.800 --> 00:31:44.160
between computational biology and then bioinformatics slash bioinformatics engineering.

00:31:44.160 --> 00:31:44.959
Right.

00:31:44.959 --> 00:31:51.040
So, you know, for so this was the case that when I was at Ceres, we had a computational

00:31:51.040 --> 00:31:54.959
biology group, which is more focused on translational analysis.

00:31:56.000 --> 00:32:00.160
And then there's the bioinformatics group, which is more focused on building the infrastructure

00:32:00.160 --> 00:32:01.359
and the algorithms.

00:32:01.359 --> 00:32:06.719
So I started out in the bioinformatics department there and sort of slowly transitioned over

00:32:06.719 --> 00:32:08.719
to the computational biology group.

00:32:09.599 --> 00:32:12.719
That is more of the distinction that I've seen in the past.

00:32:15.359 --> 00:32:15.839
Thank you.

00:32:16.719 --> 00:32:17.119
Thank you.

00:32:18.239 --> 00:32:20.000
I see, again, you asked a question.

00:32:20.000 --> 00:32:21.760
There's a little asterisk, so I'll read it.

00:32:22.560 --> 00:32:27.520
But it was how do you keep up with the technology and knowledge in the fast developing area?

00:32:28.160 --> 00:32:28.880
Yeah, that's it.

00:32:28.880 --> 00:32:30.160
I mean, that's a good question.

00:32:31.119 --> 00:32:38.880
So if so, first of all, you know, in a lot of companies, we have resources that go out

00:32:38.880 --> 00:32:44.800
and find patents and IP and interesting what appears to be, you know, interesting related

00:32:44.800 --> 00:32:47.599
publications every week or every month.

00:32:47.599 --> 00:32:49.199
And we get that kind of report.

00:32:50.319 --> 00:32:56.959
But also what has been really helpful, especially when you're in like a new field, is to

00:32:57.599 --> 00:33:00.800
just set up a ton of Google Scholar alerts.

00:33:00.800 --> 00:33:03.760
So I have Google Scholar alerts for all sorts of things.

00:33:03.760 --> 00:33:08.719
And then every, you know, it should be every day.

00:33:08.719 --> 00:33:09.839
So it's not every day.

00:33:10.560 --> 00:33:12.160
So it does pile up over time.

00:33:12.160 --> 00:33:15.040
I think I have like 90 unread ones right now.

00:33:15.040 --> 00:33:16.000
But I try, right?

00:33:16.000 --> 00:33:20.000
I try to get through the pile every couple of weeks or so.

00:33:21.040 --> 00:33:25.680
And so you can that way you can really keep on top of like cutting edge, what is being

00:33:25.680 --> 00:33:26.079
published?

00:33:26.079 --> 00:33:26.959
What are people saying?

00:33:27.760 --> 00:33:31.439
It's like the biology side, the clinical side and the technology side.

00:33:31.439 --> 00:33:37.199
I think that that is actually really helpful and low lift, except for when you're, you

00:33:37.199 --> 00:33:38.719
know, trying to go through your inbox.

00:33:41.359 --> 00:33:45.599
Yeah, I think I think that actually ties into something you and I had chatted about a little

00:33:45.599 --> 00:33:50.319
bit before, but you said in order to be the best data scientist, you can be you have to

00:33:50.319 --> 00:33:52.800
know the right questions to ask in that space.

00:33:53.520 --> 00:33:57.680
And other ways that you kind of went about that when you first started in your role.

00:33:59.920 --> 00:34:08.639
Yeah, I think that that is an area of growth that most people go through, you know, as

00:34:08.639 --> 00:34:10.719
they become more senior in their roles.

00:34:11.439 --> 00:34:17.520
So, you know, when you are fresh out of grad school, I think most of the people who, you

00:34:17.520 --> 00:34:23.360
know, when you first graduate, you have a lot of really sharp technical skills.

00:34:23.360 --> 00:34:27.600
And so you really just need someone to tell you, you know, solve this problem.

00:34:27.600 --> 00:34:30.879
Tell me, you know, very basic question.

00:34:30.879 --> 00:34:32.560
What are the differentially expressed genes?

00:34:32.560 --> 00:34:34.639
What are the pathways that are differentially expressed?

00:34:35.600 --> 00:34:36.959
And everyone can do that, right?

00:34:37.679 --> 00:34:45.520
If you're coming from a bioinformatics background, I think as you progress and you start, you

00:34:45.520 --> 00:34:51.040
know, or in my case, moving away from just the bioinformatics and going into computational

00:34:51.040 --> 00:34:53.199
biology, into the translational questions.

00:34:54.159 --> 00:35:00.879
At some point, someone like there isn't going to be someone to tell you what are the questions

00:35:00.879 --> 00:35:02.639
to ask, right?

00:35:03.199 --> 00:35:11.120
And at that point, you either, you know, need to find someone who can do that for you, or

00:35:11.120 --> 00:35:13.600
you need to start thinking of those questions yourself.

00:35:14.159 --> 00:35:22.239
I think that part can be pretty challenging because you have to understand not just what

00:35:22.239 --> 00:35:29.120
your tool set is able to answer, but what are the data that are available?

00:35:29.120 --> 00:35:35.600
You know, what are the relevant biological questions in a particular indication or in

00:35:35.600 --> 00:35:41.439
a particular space that's relevant for your company to help drive the science forward?

00:35:41.439 --> 00:35:45.919
And that, I think that takes, you know, it can take a while to learn to pick up.

00:35:46.560 --> 00:35:51.439
But I think that's where people who have the biology background, you know, people who come

00:35:51.439 --> 00:35:54.239
into bioinformatics have all different kinds of backgrounds, right?

00:35:54.239 --> 00:35:57.520
So, some people come in from a math background like myself.

00:35:57.520 --> 00:36:01.040
Some people come in from a physics or a chemistry background.

00:36:01.040 --> 00:36:07.120
And some people, I've known actually several people who come from like an ecology or a

00:36:07.120 --> 00:36:08.560
biology background.

00:36:08.560 --> 00:36:14.479
And so they actually, I think, have the benefit of having already been trying to ask those

00:36:14.479 --> 00:36:21.919
kinds of specific questions, which, you know, for someone like myself, who really avoided

00:36:21.919 --> 00:36:28.479
a lot of biology classes growing up, you know, I had to sort of learn that on the fly.

00:36:31.199 --> 00:36:31.679
Thank you.

00:36:32.479 --> 00:36:34.320
Kevin, I see you have a question in the chat.

00:36:34.320 --> 00:36:35.439
Want to ask that one next?

00:36:36.239 --> 00:36:36.800
Yeah, sure.

00:36:37.360 --> 00:36:42.159
Yeah, my question is kind of related to what you were talking about a few minutes ago about

00:36:42.159 --> 00:36:48.560
being the data science director or, you know, having a title of data scientist when you're

00:36:48.560 --> 00:36:50.399
really doing computational biology work.

00:36:51.120 --> 00:36:55.919
But yeah, I was just curious, you know, since it is a small company, do you end up getting

00:36:55.919 --> 00:37:01.120
pulled into or seeing opportunities for efficiencies in terms of like business informatics?

00:37:01.120 --> 00:37:08.159
Or, you know, I find as someone, you know, who's doing more scientific work, but having

00:37:08.159 --> 00:37:11.919
a data science background around a bunch of people who aren't data scientists, a lot of

00:37:11.919 --> 00:37:18.000
times I'll be interested in, oh, I could solve this administrative problem that people are

00:37:18.000 --> 00:37:18.800
facing, you know?

00:37:19.760 --> 00:37:22.639
And sometimes that I think is a good idea.

00:37:23.439 --> 00:37:27.360
I'm just curious, yeah, if you end up getting pulled in that direction, how you feel about

00:37:27.360 --> 00:37:30.080
that, if that's something you enjoy or something you saw as a distraction.

00:37:32.080 --> 00:37:39.520
I will say that I probably have not had that many opportunities to do that because we've

00:37:39.520 --> 00:37:46.159
had so much activity going on in the data science group that we just haven't had the

00:37:46.159 --> 00:37:47.520
bandwidth to look into that.

00:37:50.159 --> 00:37:55.199
You know, there are some examples where, but it's all like related to data science, like

00:37:55.199 --> 00:38:04.159
in terms of, you know, cleaning up our data science workspace, like our Google Cloud

00:38:04.159 --> 00:38:10.800
workspace, and working with a chemistry group, and trying to, you know, streamline things

00:38:10.800 --> 00:38:15.439
in terms of where we run our computes and how do we spend this money.

00:38:15.439 --> 00:38:19.919
That's something which is kind of an administrative task that we do get pulled into, but that's,

00:38:19.919 --> 00:38:22.159
again, still data science related, right?

00:38:22.959 --> 00:38:29.600
I guess the one example that happened kind of recently is, you know, sometimes we get,

00:38:29.600 --> 00:38:33.760
we are asked to summarize a bunch of, like, conference proceedings.

00:38:34.560 --> 00:38:39.760
And so, you know, I had at one point at my previous company, I was the only data person

00:38:39.760 --> 00:38:44.000
there, and they had sent a couple of people to different conferences, and they had brought

00:38:44.000 --> 00:38:48.959
back all of these proceedings or presentations in PDF format, and they were like, well, we

00:38:48.959 --> 00:38:52.080
want to summarize all of these things.

00:38:52.080 --> 00:38:55.199
So, there were a lot of documents and, like, hundreds of conference proceedings.

00:38:55.199 --> 00:38:59.280
And, you know, a friend of mine who is a scientist was complaining to me.

00:38:59.280 --> 00:39:03.120
She was like, well, I have to read through all of these presentations and provide a summary.

00:39:03.120 --> 00:39:06.719
And I was like, well, I could probably help you a bit with that.

00:39:06.719 --> 00:39:11.439
And so, you know, we can pull the text out of the PDF and then summarize it with, like,

00:39:11.439 --> 00:39:13.120
one of these LLMs.

00:39:13.120 --> 00:39:16.239
So, that, you know, is like a very small use case.

00:39:17.199 --> 00:39:21.520
But when we have time and there's a need, that's something that we can definitely step

00:39:21.520 --> 00:39:22.000
in to do.

00:39:23.439 --> 00:39:26.959
And do you think in the future you'll get, I don't know, you know, you could imagine

00:39:26.959 --> 00:39:32.399
doing predictive modeling for all sorts of kind of business aspects of the company, right?

00:39:32.399 --> 00:39:37.040
And that you might be the person with the skills most closely aligned with those goals,

00:39:37.040 --> 00:39:40.320
even though that's not really what your primary job is.

00:39:40.959 --> 00:39:45.280
Is that something you kind of anticipate being pulled into or maybe not?

00:39:45.280 --> 00:39:46.959
This hasn't come up yet, I guess.

00:39:46.959 --> 00:39:48.080
It hasn't come up yet.

00:39:48.800 --> 00:39:55.360
I know that, you know, there are, so, for example, a lot of analyses go into trying

00:39:55.360 --> 00:40:02.959
to find what is the next right indication to go into among, like, a choice list, right?

00:40:02.959 --> 00:40:08.560
So, let's say you have these 10 different cancers and you think that your drug could

00:40:08.560 --> 00:40:09.840
work in all of them.

00:40:09.840 --> 00:40:12.320
But what is the right market to go into?

00:40:12.320 --> 00:40:17.120
And so, you know, I've seen our BD folks work on those kinds of analyses.

00:40:18.399 --> 00:40:23.760
But that seems to me like it's very manual at the moment still, right?

00:40:23.760 --> 00:40:29.120
So, you have to do the analysis in terms of, you know, what is the patient population to

00:40:29.120 --> 00:40:29.919
begin with?

00:40:29.919 --> 00:40:33.199
And then what are the standard of care lines of therapies?

00:40:33.199 --> 00:40:37.520
And then after you whittle all of that down, you say, well, this is the patient population

00:40:37.520 --> 00:40:41.360
that we would be able to target after you account for all of these things.

00:40:41.360 --> 00:40:46.159
And then trying to figure out, you know, what is the right market in terms of the size

00:40:46.159 --> 00:40:50.560
of the patient, like the treatable patient population that you go into.

00:40:50.560 --> 00:40:53.760
But I've only seen the output of those kinds of analyses.

00:40:53.760 --> 00:40:57.679
I haven't seen what goes into it and sort of where they pull those data from.

00:40:58.239 --> 00:41:03.199
But it sounds to me like that's probably very manual, like a manual search kind of

00:41:03.199 --> 00:41:03.699
thing.

00:41:04.560 --> 00:41:08.239
You mean like it has to be manual or it just is currently manual?

00:41:08.239 --> 00:41:08.959
It has been.

00:41:08.959 --> 00:41:09.840
Yeah, it has been.

00:41:09.840 --> 00:41:10.340
Yeah.

00:41:10.820 --> 00:41:11.320
Yeah.

00:41:11.620 --> 00:41:12.120
Okay.

00:41:12.659 --> 00:41:13.060
All right.

00:41:13.060 --> 00:41:13.459
Thanks.

00:41:13.459 --> 00:41:13.959
Thanks.

00:41:16.179 --> 00:41:20.979
I see Bill asked, it was a follow-up question when we were talking about algorithms.

00:41:20.979 --> 00:41:25.139
And Bill had asked, what role does R and Python play in your workflow?

00:41:27.860 --> 00:41:29.219
We're all Python here.

00:41:30.179 --> 00:41:32.419
I was all R for many, many years.

00:41:33.620 --> 00:41:37.939
I think it really depends on the kind of analysis that you're doing.

00:41:38.820 --> 00:41:45.699
So my personal preference is, you know, when we're writing pipelines and doing data processing,

00:41:45.699 --> 00:41:46.899
that's all done in Python.

00:41:47.860 --> 00:41:53.300
I'm really familiar with R in terms of the data analysis side and making figures and

00:41:53.300 --> 00:41:54.179
reports and things.

00:41:54.179 --> 00:41:56.739
So I really love Posit for that.

00:41:57.379 --> 00:41:59.060
You've been using it for a very long time.

00:42:00.739 --> 00:42:03.219
But it's our day-to-day, right?

00:42:03.219 --> 00:42:07.780
Every day we open up notebooks and do these kinds of analyses, whether in Jupyter or

00:42:08.179 --> 00:42:08.679
R.

00:42:11.699 --> 00:42:12.199
Thank you.

00:42:14.580 --> 00:42:19.379
Jazz, I want to make sure your question, it may have been answered in another one,

00:42:19.379 --> 00:42:22.500
but if not, I want to make sure you have an opportunity to jump in.

00:42:25.699 --> 00:42:31.139
I think it was about roles to suggest for someone with, let me, and you can jump in

00:42:31.139 --> 00:42:35.620
if you want to add more context, but it was what roles can someone suggest for a life

00:42:35.620 --> 00:42:41.939
science business analyst with a math and biomedical science degree to make a transition

00:42:41.939 --> 00:42:43.379
into bioinformatics?

00:42:44.659 --> 00:42:47.139
Oh, to transition into bioinformatics.

00:42:49.379 --> 00:42:50.580
Jazz, I see you've unmuted.

00:42:50.580 --> 00:42:51.300
Do you want to jump in?

00:42:52.100 --> 00:42:56.419
Yeah, so I have 10 years of experience in healthcare analytics.

00:42:56.419 --> 00:43:02.739
So it has been somewhat business analytics, but it's also been healthcare information.

00:43:03.300 --> 00:43:09.300
But I see bioinformatics more towards the science side of things.

00:43:09.300 --> 00:43:14.179
So, you know, making use of, say, biomedical science knowledge, but I haven't really been

00:43:14.179 --> 00:43:14.979
doing that.

00:43:14.979 --> 00:43:21.939
So I just wondered how easy would it be for someone to jump away from business analytics

00:43:21.939 --> 00:43:29.459
into more bioinformatics and what kind of roles, because I think, I mean, it's easy

00:43:29.459 --> 00:43:35.139
to sort of just put in bioinformatics analyst, but I find that they require MSc.

00:43:36.979 --> 00:43:40.500
So are there any other roles that I could make that transition?

00:43:43.860 --> 00:43:51.459
Yeah, I mean, I think it really depends on your current skill set and where you could

00:43:51.459 --> 00:43:58.979
jump in and sort of start working, essentially, from day one.

00:43:59.620 --> 00:44:07.540
So, you know, if you are already familiar with, you know, R or Python to run some analyses,

00:44:07.540 --> 00:44:11.699
you know, it doesn't really matter what kind of data are coming in, right?

00:44:11.699 --> 00:44:15.540
As long as you understand sort of what the distribution looks like, you know, what does

00:44:15.540 --> 00:44:16.500
the data represent?

00:44:16.500 --> 00:44:17.939
Those are all things that you can learn.

00:44:20.100 --> 00:44:24.419
I think it's really making the case for whatever role you're looking into.

00:44:24.419 --> 00:44:31.139
I would assume if you don't have like a master's, you're probably looking at starting as a research

00:44:31.139 --> 00:44:39.219
associate level to make the case that you would be able to pick up these skills, given

00:44:39.219 --> 00:44:41.939
what you're already, like what you have already been able to do.

00:44:43.699 --> 00:44:47.139
You know, I think that you probably have a better chance.

00:44:48.179 --> 00:44:50.100
Well, it's actually hard to say.

00:44:50.100 --> 00:44:53.300
You know, I want to say that you probably have a better chance at a smaller company,

00:44:53.300 --> 00:44:56.340
but it really depends on the company and what they're looking for in a role.

00:44:58.020 --> 00:45:03.060
You know, I think in a larger company, maybe you have a little bit more leeway in terms

00:45:03.060 --> 00:45:11.540
of, you know, having like having the opportunity to learn skills, like a little bit more time

00:45:11.540 --> 00:45:15.860
to learn skills on the job, whereas smaller companies want you to really be able to hit

00:45:15.860 --> 00:45:17.379
the ground running on day one.

00:45:18.899 --> 00:45:22.419
But I think that probably also varies by company and role.

00:45:23.139 --> 00:45:31.780
So it's really like trying to find the right match, like the right role for you, given

00:45:31.780 --> 00:45:34.179
your background, what you want and what the company needs.

00:45:37.939 --> 00:45:38.419
Yeah, thank you.

00:45:38.419 --> 00:45:39.139
That answers the question.

00:45:40.020 --> 00:45:40.340
Thank you.

00:45:42.500 --> 00:45:47.459
I know we've had a few different career type questions here, so I want to make sure I ask

00:45:47.459 --> 00:45:48.260
this as well.

00:45:48.260 --> 00:45:53.939
Is there a specific piece of career advice that you've either given to other people or

00:45:53.939 --> 00:45:56.419
that you've received that stands out in your mind?

00:46:03.139 --> 00:46:13.300
Yeah, I mean, so I think personally speaking, the most important thing to me is to not be

00:46:13.300 --> 00:46:16.100
afraid to make the leap into something new.

00:46:17.060 --> 00:46:22.659
Every time I started, I have started a new job, I have been terrified that it's not going

00:46:22.659 --> 00:46:25.139
to work out or I'm not going to have the skills.

00:46:26.100 --> 00:46:28.419
This happened when I was going to grad school.

00:46:28.419 --> 00:46:30.340
It happened when I moved my postdoc.

00:46:30.340 --> 00:46:33.939
It happened when I was, you know, looking for my new job and my second job and my third

00:46:33.939 --> 00:46:35.300
job every single time.

00:46:36.580 --> 00:46:44.179
I think this is where it's really important to know for yourself internally what you think

00:46:44.179 --> 00:46:45.780
you're capable of doing.

00:46:46.659 --> 00:46:51.699
Right, so yes, you have to convince someone else to hire you that you're capable of doing

00:46:51.699 --> 00:46:54.659
what you say, but you also have to know that.

00:46:54.659 --> 00:47:02.580
And so I think once you are comfortable with that, it makes it, you know, then you don't

00:47:02.580 --> 00:47:06.899
fear as much the unknown of what the new job is going to look like.

00:47:06.899 --> 00:47:11.139
It's more that you know that it's going to be, you know, challenging for a couple of

00:47:11.139 --> 00:47:15.699
weeks or a couple of months as you start up, but that you're going to get there and it's

00:47:15.699 --> 00:47:16.500
going to be fine.

00:47:18.739 --> 00:47:20.179
Yeah, I think fear is natural.

00:47:21.060 --> 00:47:27.459
Being nervous is natural, but I think that, you know, people are able to overcome that.

00:47:30.020 --> 00:47:30.659
I love that.

00:47:30.659 --> 00:47:31.379
Thank you very much.

00:47:33.139 --> 00:47:37.780
Something that you said to me also, which was like sticking with me is a boss said to

00:47:37.780 --> 00:47:43.219
you before, in an ideal world, what would you have accomplished five years from now

00:47:43.219 --> 00:47:44.179
in an interview?

00:47:44.260 --> 00:47:48.500
And I thought that was, it's just, I've just been thinking a lot about it too.

00:47:48.500 --> 00:47:51.459
So I was wondering if you could share that story with everybody.

00:47:51.459 --> 00:47:57.459
Yeah, so I was, so this was for my very first job.

00:47:57.459 --> 00:48:00.100
I'd never had a, like a job job before.

00:48:00.100 --> 00:48:01.699
So I was a postdoc.

00:48:01.699 --> 00:48:02.659
I was interviewing.

00:48:02.659 --> 00:48:07.219
I was really excited for this opportunity because in my postdoc, I had been studying

00:48:07.219 --> 00:48:12.899
the microbiome and then I had this opportunity through a recruiter to work at a microbiome

00:48:12.899 --> 00:48:13.939
therapeutics company.

00:48:15.060 --> 00:48:17.620
I knew zero about drug discovery.

00:48:17.620 --> 00:48:18.260
I knew nothing.

00:48:19.620 --> 00:48:26.020
So, you know, the, the, my hiring manager who later became my boss, she asked me like

00:48:26.020 --> 00:48:32.179
the last question before the end of the interviews, she was like, well, in an ideal world, you

00:48:32.179 --> 00:48:35.540
know, what would you like to have accomplished five years from now?

00:48:36.260 --> 00:48:40.100
And I like, I really hate that question because like, you know, what do you, what do you know?

00:48:40.100 --> 00:48:42.020
What, what's life going to look like in five years?

00:48:42.020 --> 00:48:42.659
Nobody knows.

00:48:44.580 --> 00:48:50.500
So I was thinking to myself, I was like, well, you know, what, what, what would be really

00:48:50.500 --> 00:48:58.020
cool is if I could be part of the team that brought the first like microbiome therapeutic

00:48:58.020 --> 00:48:58.820
to the market.

00:48:59.699 --> 00:49:06.500
I had no idea how unlikely of a, of a, of a goal that could be.

00:49:07.620 --> 00:49:11.379
I didn't know what timelines look like in drug discovery.

00:49:12.979 --> 00:49:16.979
And, you know, five years is not a, not a very long time.

00:49:16.979 --> 00:49:23.139
And we were working on a novel therapeutic and a novel space, nothing like no microbiome

00:49:23.139 --> 00:49:25.459
therapeutic had been approved before.

00:49:27.060 --> 00:49:32.899
But I, you know, what I like about this story is it kind of showcases, you know, when you

00:49:32.899 --> 00:49:40.580
are new to an industry and you don't necessarily know what to expect, that you can kind of

00:49:40.580 --> 00:49:47.060
aim for anything and, you know, not be held back by your preconceived notions of what's

00:49:47.060 --> 00:49:47.540
possible.

00:49:48.659 --> 00:49:53.540
And it, as it turned out, like five years later, after being at that company, five and

00:49:53.540 --> 00:49:59.459
a half years later, we were actually on track to, to FDA approval for that therapeutic.

00:49:59.459 --> 00:50:01.060
It's really amazing.

00:50:01.060 --> 00:50:06.659
It's like kind of an incredible Cinderella story, which I love to tell because actually

00:50:06.659 --> 00:50:10.899
I'm going to add a little bit to that, to that story, which is when I started that job,

00:50:11.939 --> 00:50:19.620
I started on Monday and on the Friday of my first week and my first job ever, we got this

00:50:19.620 --> 00:50:24.820
really, really terrible news that our phase two trial had completely flopped.

00:50:24.820 --> 00:50:26.020
It was for the same program.

00:50:27.379 --> 00:50:35.060
And you can feel like the, the disappointment and the heartbreak was really palpable in

00:50:35.060 --> 00:50:36.260
the room, right?

00:50:36.260 --> 00:50:42.979
Everybody had worked so hard on this program and the results were so bad.

00:50:42.979 --> 00:50:43.780
There was like nothing.

00:50:43.780 --> 00:50:44.820
There's no signal at all.

00:50:46.500 --> 00:50:50.580
And I thought I was like going to not have a job on Monday, basically.

00:50:51.860 --> 00:50:58.260
But somehow really, I think, attesting to the scientific leadership, you know, everyone

00:50:58.260 --> 00:51:03.699
really, really dug down deep and I was fortunate to be a part of this effort.

00:51:04.659 --> 00:51:09.379
We went back, looked at the data, reanalyzed the data, built new algorithms, you know,

00:51:09.379 --> 00:51:15.860
built new software, got new data to, to really figure out what happened to identify all of

00:51:15.860 --> 00:51:19.780
the issues that led to that failed phase two trial.

00:51:19.780 --> 00:51:24.580
And we didn't, when we went back to the FDA, we didn't have to rerun the phase two trial.

00:51:24.580 --> 00:51:30.100
We justified like what we, you know, what we had found and what, why we thought we saw

00:51:30.179 --> 00:51:34.739
what we did in the phase two and we were able to proceed to a phase three trial.

00:51:35.459 --> 00:51:37.699
It was really an amazing story.

00:51:39.459 --> 00:51:40.500
I love that story.

00:51:40.500 --> 00:51:40.979
Thank you.

00:51:42.260 --> 00:51:43.699
I know we have a few minutes left here.

00:51:43.699 --> 00:51:46.260
I want to make sure I get to all the questions.

00:51:46.260 --> 00:51:47.540
Matthew, I see your hands raised.

00:51:47.540 --> 00:51:48.179
Want to jump in?

00:51:52.419 --> 00:51:53.780
You might be muted still.

00:51:56.580 --> 00:51:59.699
Okay, I'll jump over to another one, but I see your hand still up.

00:51:59.860 --> 00:52:03.459
If you unmute, feel free to go next.

00:52:05.780 --> 00:52:06.419
Let's see.

00:52:07.139 --> 00:52:15.060
Oh, Nathan had a question just about the microbiome therapy and just more details on that,

00:52:15.060 --> 00:52:17.540
if that was the same as fecal transplant.

00:52:18.500 --> 00:52:19.300
Different.

00:52:19.300 --> 00:52:20.739
It's actually an oral pill.

00:52:21.540 --> 00:52:29.060
So FMT, this fecal microbiota transplantation, this is something that has existed for,

00:52:29.060 --> 00:52:33.620
for several years, for a long time for the treatment of recurrent C. diff.

00:52:35.379 --> 00:52:42.820
This was a procedure that was not regulated by the FDA, but it is like very efficacious

00:52:42.820 --> 00:52:45.300
for the treatment of C. diff infections.

00:52:46.260 --> 00:52:52.979
So what Ceres was trying to do was to make this kind of a regulated, a clean, clean process,

00:52:52.979 --> 00:53:00.340
because an FMT is really just like a fecal enema, which nobody really wants to have done.

00:53:01.860 --> 00:53:09.219
And so what Ceres was developing was this pill, which was derived, which is derived from

00:53:10.419 --> 00:53:15.219
healthy patient stool samples that has been heavily, heavily processed, so that all that

00:53:15.219 --> 00:53:19.860
remains are these bacterial spores from commensal bacteria.

00:53:20.580 --> 00:53:24.260
And so I've actually seen those pills that are like, you know, just like a normal pill,

00:53:24.260 --> 00:53:24.979
little blue pill.

00:53:26.020 --> 00:53:29.699
And it's just packed full of healthy bacterial spores.

00:53:30.260 --> 00:53:34.820
And as, as, you know, one of the scientists who got to analyze the clinical data, what you see

00:53:35.459 --> 00:53:42.580
is when patients take this pill, they start out with a very dysbiotic microbiome, because this

00:53:42.580 --> 00:53:44.100
is, these are patients who are really sick.

00:53:44.100 --> 00:53:45.939
They've taken lots of antibiotics.

00:53:45.939 --> 00:53:49.699
Those antibiotics have really destroyed their gut microbiome.

00:53:49.699 --> 00:53:50.500
There's nothing there.

00:53:51.459 --> 00:53:58.340
And within like two to three days of taking this pill, the microbiome is just like,

00:53:58.340 --> 00:53:59.620
it's blossoming back.

00:53:59.620 --> 00:54:02.500
It's really, it's really incredible to see the kinetics.

