00:54:50.739 --> 00:54:54.820
throwing around this generative AI idea in the drug development space.

00:54:55.620 --> 00:55:01.860
And what I have found is that in general, there's a lot of hype and not a lot of results,

00:55:03.300 --> 00:55:06.020
specifically when you're talking about gen AI, right?

00:55:06.739 --> 00:55:16.899
And I also think that over time, what people call what I would call just statistics and

00:55:16.899 --> 00:55:19.219
analysis has changed.

00:55:19.219 --> 00:55:23.860
So, you know, seven years ago, it was, what are we doing with machine learning?

00:55:23.860 --> 00:55:25.860
This, you know, someone talking to me, right?

00:55:25.860 --> 00:55:30.340
And then, you know, five years ago, it's like, what are we doing with, you know, deep learning?

00:55:30.340 --> 00:55:32.179
And now it's like, what are we doing with AI?

00:55:32.820 --> 00:55:40.739
And I think that for the kinds of analyses we do, the technology is not there yet for that.

00:55:42.260 --> 00:55:50.020
I think it's different in the chemistry space where you have a lot of data points going in

00:55:50.020 --> 00:55:52.179
and you have a lot of screens being run.

00:55:52.739 --> 00:55:57.219
So you have something that you can run on, that you can generate these models on.

00:55:57.860 --> 00:56:05.139
When you're talking about like microbiome patient data in like any kind of clinical

00:56:05.139 --> 00:56:11.219
trial, honestly, the sample sizes aren't large enough to build those kinds of models.

00:56:11.219 --> 00:56:14.979
And I don't think that people have a clear idea of really of even what are the right

00:56:14.979 --> 00:56:17.060
questions to ask with those kinds of models.

